# Page Object Model rules

## Class shape
- Every page MUST extend `BasePage` (`src/pages/base_page.py`).
- The class constructor takes a single `Page` argument plus optional dependencies.
- Selectors are defined as **class-level constants** (UPPER_SNAKE) at the top of the class.
- Each public method describes a single user action: `search(query)`, `add_to_cart()`, `get_subtotal()`. Avoid generic `click_button(name)`.

## What pages may NOT do
- **No assertions.** Pages return data; tests assert.
- **No Allure decorators.** Pages emit screenshots; tests own the steps.
- **No `time.sleep`.** Use Playwright auto-wait, `wait_for_load_state`, or `wait_for(state=...)`.
- **No reaching across pages.** A page must not import another page (only components/utils). Cross-page orchestration lives in `src/flows/`.

## Components
- Components live in `src/components/` and wrap reusable widgets (header, filter, paginator, card).
- A component is constructed with the same `Page` reference the parent page holds.
- Components follow the same "no assertions, no sleeps" rules as pages.

## Selector strategy (in order of preference)
1. `page.get_by_role("button", name="Add to cart")`
2. `page.get_by_test_id("add-to-cart")`
3. `page.get_by_text("Add to cart", exact=True)`
4. CSS attribute selectors (`button[name='add']`)
5. XPath - only when previous strategies fail or when the brief mandates XPath (case in point: `SearchResultsPage.PRODUCT_CARD_XPATH`).

When a selector is fragile, store **multiple candidates as a tuple** and iterate in `_first_visible(...)` style - already done in `LoginPage`, `PriceFilter`, `Paginator`. This is the pattern to follow.

## Adding a new page
1. Create `src/pages/<name>_page.py`. Extend `BasePage`.
2. Define `URL_PATH` if applicable.
3. Add selector constants at the top of the class.
4. Expose user-action methods (`open()`, `click_x`, `read_y`).
5. Re-export from `src/pages/__init__.py`.
6. If the page introduces a reusable widget, extract it into `src/components/`.
